Megaloblasts present in bone marrow AND Oval macrocytes on the blood smear.

Megaloblastic states result from defective DNA synthesis. However, RNA synthesis continues, resulting in a large cell with a large nucleus.
Therefore, characteristically, megaloblasts in the bone marrow have immature nuclei compared to the degree of cytoplasmic maturation.
Howell-Jolly bodies (DNA remnants) may be present.

1. When methylene THF is used for this purpose, it is converted to methyl-THF. This is unusable.

  1. The methyl THF is recycled to THF so that it can be reconverted to methylene THF and more DNA can be made.
  2. This recylding of methyl THF requires action of the methionine synthase reaction for which B12 is a cofactor.
    Deficiency of B12 and Folate both result in deficiency of methylene THF and therefore, defiency of DNA sythesis -> megaloblastic anaemia

Treatment of B12 and folate deficiency

If large doses of folate are given in B12 deficiency, neuropathy can be worsened!.
B9 (folate) should not be given alone unless B12 deficiency is excluded.
B12 is given IM and B9 is given orally.

Reticulocytes and assessment of erythropoiesis

Erythropoiesis

The first recognisable RBC precursor is the pronormoblast.
Once the nucleus is extruded, a reticulocyte results. They only have cytoplasmic RNA. No DNA.
Reticulocytes still have RNA so they can still synthesize haemoglobin. They circulate in the blood for 1-2 days before maturing and losing all RNA.

In intact erythropoiesis, reticulocyte count increases in proportion to the anaemia.
Erythropoiesis is stimulated by EPo which is produced by the peritubular, interstitial cells of the kidney in response to reduced oxygen delivery.
Timescale: after acute haemorrhage, EPO increases by 6 hours, retic count begins to increase in 2-3 days and peaks by 6-10 days and stays elevated until the Hb returns to normal.
Normal retic count - 0.5 - 2.5%

Mechanism of EPo

EPo increases the number of progenitor cells committed to erythrypoiesis.
In the chronic state, there is anatomical expansion of erythropoiesis into fatty marrow and even into extramedullar sites.

Sepsis

Source

[!INFO] Definition of Sepsis
A life-threatening organ dysfunction that develops as a result of impaired host response to infection.
In addition to the proven infection, a score of 2 or more points on the SOFA (organ dysfunction) is required for the diagnosis of sepsis
Source
Source

Hour 1 bundle

Sepsis is a medical emergency!
Upon recognition of sepsis:

  1. Measure lactate level
  2. Obtain blood cultures prior to antibiotics
  3. Give broad spectrum antibiotics
  4. Begin rapid administration of 30ml/Kg crystalloid for hypotension OR lactate > 4mmol/L.
  5. Apply vasopressors if hypotensive during or after fluid resuscitation to maintain MAP > 65mmHg.

Fluid:
Balanced crystalloid is better than normal saline. N/S caries a risk of hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis.

Vasopressors:

  • Central access is preferred but as line placement can cause delays, it's safe to give peripheral vasopressors for periods < 6 hours. (concerns are due to extravsation and local tissue injury).
  • Noradrenaline is recommended as the first line vasopressor.

IV corticosteroids:
Systemic corticosteroid accelerate resolution of shock.

Early identification of sepsis

Using qSOFA alone is no longer recommended.
"most" have poor predictive values.

systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) criteria are superior to qSOFA for the clinical diagnosis of sepsis, and qSOFA is superior to SIRS for predicting in-hospital mortality - Source

SIRS score

SIRS is diagnosed by the presence of at least two of the following four SIRS criteria:

  1. body temperature > 38°C or < 36°C,
  2. heart rate > 90 beats/min,
  3. respiratory rate > 20 breaths/min or PaCO2< 32 mm Hg,
  4. leukocyte count over 12,000mm−3 or under 4,000mm−3 or immature band/neutrophil ratio exceeds 10%.

Alcohol withdrawal

Pathophsiology

Alcohol withdrawal occurs upon abrupt cessation of prolonged, sustained ethanol intake.

Abrupt cessation unmasks the adaptive responses to chronic ethanol use, resulting in overactivity of the central nervous system.

Alochol is a CNS depressant.

  • It enhances GABA mediated inhibitory tone
  • Suppresses excitatory tone.

Alcohol stimulates GABA but also makes the GABA receptors less sensitive with chronic use.
A few weeks of continued usage is sufficient for this effect.
When alcohol is stopped, GABA decreases but the desensitized receptors remain -> overall result is that the CNS is now insensitive to GABA -> overall increased excitation.

Glutamate is one of the major excitatory amino acids.
Glutamade binds to the NMDA receptor -> calcium influx -> neuronal excitation.
This is inhibited by alcohol.
Adaptation occurs by increasing the expression of glutamate receptors; this adaptation is unmasked when alcohol with withdrawn -> hyperexcitability.

Physiological effects of alcohol

Increased opiate levels -> euphoria
Increases GABA -> anxiolytic and sedative effects.
Inhibits glutamate receptor -> chonic use leads to glutamate receptor upregulation -> increased CNS excitability when alcohol is withdrawn.
Neuronal death in the brain due to chornic alcohol use -> crebellar degeneration.

Alcohol withdrawal occurs in those who have maintained high intake for years and who maintain binges for weeks at a time.

[!INFO] Predicting risk of withdrawal
The best predictor for clinically significant alcohol withdrawal is a Prediction of Alcohol Withdrawal Severity Scale (PAWSS) score

  • A score of ≥4 suggests high risk for moderate to severe AWS; prophylaxis and/or treatment may be indicated

Symptoms of withdrawal

  • Tremors of hands and legs
  • Nausea and retching
  • Sweating and tachycardia
  • Hallucinations
  • Epileptic seizures
  • After about 48 hours -> delerium tremens.

Withdrawal seizures

Usually occur within 12 - 48 hours after the last drink.
Usually singular seizures or group of seizures over a short time. (recurrent, prolonged seizures or status epilepticus are not typical of alcohol withdrawal seizures.
Management

  1. Phenytoin it NOT effective
  2. benzodiazepines -> phenobarbital -> porpofol should be used.

[!TIP] Alcohol withdrawal seizures can be managed with phenoBARBIEtone

[!INFO] Alcohol withdrawal seizures if untreated will progress to delerium tremens in 1/3 of cases

Alcoholic hallucinosis

NOT THE SAME THING as delerium tremens.
Alcoholic hallucinosis refers to hallucinations that develop within 12 to 24 hours of abstinence and typically resolve within 24 to 48 hours. (i.e before DT usually begins).

Usually visual; auditory hallucinations aren't impossible.
Patients continue to have insight about the hallucinations, so they are usually distressed.

Delerium tremens

rapid-onset, fluctuating disturbance of attention and cognition, sometimes with hallucinations, in the presence of alcohol withdrawal

  • accompanied by agitation and signs of extreme autonomic hyperactivity,
  • including fever,
  • severe tachycardia,
  • hypertension,
  • and drenching sweats

Patients with DT have significantly elevated cardiac indixes, oxygen delivery, and oxygen consumption.
Hyperventilation is present -> causes hypocapnia -> decreased cerebral blood flow.

Other associated problems:

  • Hypovolemia - vomitting, sweating, poor intake
  • Metabolic acidosis - alcoholic ketoacidosis, hypoperfusion, or thiamine deficiency. (See [[causesOfLacticAcidosis.png]]
  • hypokalemia - renal and extra renal pottasium losses; aldosterone alterations
  • hypomagnesemia - predisposes to arrhythmia
  • hypophophatemia - results from mulnutrition.

[!WARNING] CAUSES OF DEATH
Death usually is due to dysrhythmia, complicating illnesses such as pneumonia, or failure to identify an underlying problem that led to the cessation of alcohol use, such as pancreatitis, hepatitis, or central nervous system injury or infection.

Treatment

Supportive - benzodiazepines to prevent progression of withdrawal symptoms.
IV benzodiazepines if required.

Prophylactic chlordiazepoxide can be used if high risk of withdrawal in a patient admitted for other reasons.
